'''''The Sceptical Feminist: A Philosophical Enquiry''''' (1980; second edition 1994) is a book about feminism by the philosopher [[Janet Radcliffe Richards]].

==Summary==
Richards argues against both opponents of feminism as well as much "common feminist dogma and practice."{{sfn|Richards|1994|page=21}}

==Publication history==
''The Sceptical Feminist'' was first published by [[Routledge|Routledge and Kegan Paul]] in 1980. In 1982, it was published in [[Pelican Books]]. In 1991, it was reprinted in [[Penguin Books]]. In 1994, the book was published with a new introduction and two new appendices.{{sfn|Richards|1994|page=4}}

==Reception==
''The Sceptical Feminist'' has been influential, but it has been criticized for being "too unworldly in its understanding of women's oppression, and insufficiently radical in the remedies it proposes." Susan Mendus writes that Richards provides little discussion of inequalities of power which perpetuate injustice, and accepts that "women's work" is less fulfilling and valuable than work outside the home, commenting, "Richards's feminism is logical rather than ideological, cerebral rather than celebratory."{{sfn|Mendus|2005|page=781}} The book was controversial within and outside feminism, in regard to standards of rationality,{{sfn|Battersby|1991|page=200}} fashion and style, and Richards' liberal stance.{{sfn|Whelehan|1995|pages=39–40}}

The philosopher [[Christina Hoff Sommers]] expressed agreement with some of Richards' arguments in ''[[Who Stole Feminism?]]'' (1994).{{sfn|Sommers|1994|pages=27, 278}}

''The Sceptical Feminist'' received a positive review from the philosopher [[Antony Flew]] in ''[[The Philosophical Quarterly]]''.{{sfn|Flew|1981|page=380}} The book was also reviewed by Emily Stoper in ''[[Journal of Women, Politics & Policy|Women & Politics]]'',{{sfn|Stoper|1983|pages=77–78}} and Christa Bausch in ''Sociology & Social Research''.{{sfn|Bausch|1985|pages=274–275}}

Flew considered the book excellent and probably the best book on its topic, and its material relevant to questions of ethics in general as well as specifically to feminism. However, he considered one chapter "marred" to some extent by the intrusion of [[John Rawls]]'s ideas about justice, which in his view Richards had not fully understood, and criticized Richards for not devoting more space to criticizing Marxist feminists.{{sfn|Flew|1981|page=380}}

