'''Vanity sizing''', or '''size inflation''', is the phenomenon of [[ready-to-wear]] clothing of the same [[nominal size]] becoming bigger in physical size over time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,57672,00.html|title=Flattery Gets Designers Everywhere|date=15 July 2002|publisher=}}</ref><ref name="newsweek"/><ref name="fox"/> This has been documented primarily in the [[United States]] and the [[United Kingdom]].<ref>https://www.al/story.asp?S=1771013&nav=1aI8M8qf</ref> [[United States|US]] standard clothing sizes are no longer used by manufacturers as the official guidelines for clothing sizes was abandoned in 1983.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sites.wp.odu.edu/bodylore/2018/03/01/hidden-numbers-the-history-of-womens-clothing-sizes-in-the-u-s/|title=Hidden Numbers: The History of Women’s Clothing Sizes in the U.S. {{!}} Bodylore|website=sites.wp.odu.edu|language=en-US|access-date=2018-09-20}}</ref><!--{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}-->{{cbignore|bot=medic}}{{verify source|date=April 2013}} In the United States, although clothing size standards exist (i.e., [[ASTM]]), most companies do not use them any longer.<ref name=newsweek>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newsweek.com/fashion-designers-introduce-less-zero-sizes-112005|title=Fashion Designers Introduce Less-than-Zero Sizes |date=17 October 2006|work=Newsweek|access-date=2018-12-01|language=en|last=Schrobsdorff |first=Susanna}}</ref>
Size inconsistency has existed since at least 1937. In [[Sears]]'s 1937 catalog, a [[dress size|size]] 14 dress had a bust size of {{convert|32|in|cm}}. In 1967, the same bust size was a size 8. In 2011, it was a [[size 0]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Clifford|first=Stepanie|title=One Size Fits Nobody: Seeking a Steady 4 or a 10|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/04/25/business/25sizing.html?_r=1|accessdate=13 July 2011|newspaper=New York Times|date=24 April 2011}}</ref> Some argue that vanity sizing is designed to satisfy wearers' wishes to appear thin and feel better about themselves.<ref name="newsweek"/><ref name="fox">{{cite news| url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,57672,00.html | work=Fox News | title=Flattery Gets Designers Everywhere | first=Jennifer | last=D'Angelo | date=15 July 2002}}</ref> This works by adhering to the theory of compensatory self-enhancement, as vanity sizing promotes a more positive self-image of one upon seeing a smaller label.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sites.wp.odu.edu/bodylore/2018/03/01/hidden-numbers-the-history-of-womens-clothing-sizes-in-the-u-s/|title=Hidden Numbers: The History of Women’s Clothing Sizes in the U.S. {{!}} Bodylore|website=sites.wp.odu.edu|language=en-US|access-date=2018-09-20}}</ref> Designer [[Nicole Miller]] introduced size 0 because of its strong California presence and to satisfy the request of many Asian customers. It introduced subzero sizes for naturally petite women.<ref name="newsweek"/> However, the increasing size of clothing with the same nominal size caused Nicole Miller to introduce size 0, 00, or subzero sizes.<ref name="newsweek"/> The UK's [[Chief Medical Officer (United Kingdom)|Chief Medical Officer]] has suggested that vanity sizing has contributed to the normalisation of obesity in society.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Howard |first=SJ |last2=Davies |first2=Sally C |date=27 March 2014 |title=Chief medical officer urges action to tackle overweight and obesity |url=http://www.bmj.com/content/348/bmj.g2375 |journal=BMJ |volume=348 |doi=10.1136/bmj.g2375 |access-date=7 May 2016 |pmid=24677657 |pages=g2375}}</ref>
In 2003, a study that measured over 1,000 pairs of women's [[pants]] found that pants from more expensive brands tended to be smaller than those from cheaper brands with the same nominal size.<ref>Kinley, TR (2003). [http://ctr.sagepub.com/cgi/content/refs/21/1/19 "Clothing Size Variation in Women's Pants"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061019070457/http://ctr.sagepub.com/cgi/content/refs/21/1/19 |date=19 October 2006 }}. ''Clothing and Textiles Research Journal''. '''21''' (1): 19&ndash;31. Subscription required.</ref>
